Java Varargs.evidence:
Java introduced variable-length arguments, commonly known as varargs, in version 5. This feature allows methods to accept a variable number of arguments of a specified type, simplifying method declarations and enhancing code readability. ([docs.oracle.com](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/varargs.html?utm_source=openai))

Prior to Java 5, developers had to use method overloading or pass arrays to handle methods requiring a variable number of arguments. Varargs provide a more concise and flexible approach by enabling methods to accept zero or more arguments of a specified type. ([docs.oracle.com](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/varargs.html?utm_source=openai))

To define a varargs method, you use an ellipsis (`...`) followed by the parameter type in the method signature. For example, a method that accepts a variable number of integers can be declared as:

```java
public void myMethod(int... numbers) {
    // Method body
}
```

Inside the method, the varargs parameter is treated as an array, allowing you to iterate over the arguments as needed. ([docs.oracle.com](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/varargs.html?utm_source=openai))

It's important to note that a method can have only one varargs parameter, and it must be the last parameter in the method's parameter list. This ensures clarity and prevents ambiguity in method calls. ([docs.oracle.com](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/varargs.html?utm_source=openai))

